WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBC LearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello and welcome to 6-minute English from BBC LearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.000
I'm Pippa and I'm Beth. Have you ever been scared of speaking in English?

5
00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:23.000
In this episode we're talking about why speaking in a foreign language can be so stressful.

6
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So Pippa, do you ever get nervous speaking in a different language?

7
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Yes, I learned French when I was younger and I was actually quite good at it, I think, but I was really nervous when I was speaking French.

8
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.000
How about you?

9
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Yeah, I've always felt like that would Spanish. I'm scared to speak because I don't want to make mistakes.

10
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Even though I know it's okay to make mistakes.

11
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Well, in this episode of 6-minute English, we'll be hearing about how to feel less nervous when you speak English.

12
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases.

13
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
You can practice these with the quiz and worksheets on our website, BBCLannyEnglish.com

14
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
But first, I have a question for you, Pippa.

15
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
So English has around 1 million words.

16
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But on average, how many words does a typical English speaker use in daily conversation?

17
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Is it a between 2000 and 3000?

18
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.000
B between 20,000 and 30,000?

19
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Or C between 200,000 and 300,000?

20
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
I'm going to say a 2003,000.

21
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Okay, well, we will find out later in the program.

22
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Now, Pippa, you said you found it stressful speaking in French, even though you are quite good at it.

23
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Now, someone else who has had this experience is Hanan Razak.

24
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Hanan is a Jan-List at BBC Arabic and also host of the podcast, Bating, Speaking, Anxiety.

25
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Here she is, telling BBCLannyEnglish presented Georgie about speaking English.

26
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.000
My English was actually pretty good, but having conversations with people, I found it really difficult.

27
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
So when I first joined the BBC, the learning English team made an assessment of my English level,

28
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
which they used to do for all new joiners to see if they need any help or courses.

29
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:29.000
My results were pretty good and I was fluent, but on that very same day, leaving the building and going to get some coffee,

30
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.000
I couldn't really understand what the barista was saying.

31
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
And I felt pretty nervous to order coffee and was trying to stress every single word,

32
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
hoping that my grammar is correct and I am pronouncing the words right.

33
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I'm sure that's a situation lots of people can relate to.

34
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Hanan's results on her English assessment were pretty good, but she was still pretty nervous to speak in English,

35
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:55.000
for example, when ordering a coffee in English.

36
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:59.000
The modifier pretty means quite or a bit.

37
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Georgie says that Hanan's experience is something that lots of people can relate to.

38
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:11.000
If you relate to a situation, you know what it feels like, usually because a similar thing has happened to you.

39
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:18.000
So lots of people feel nervous speaking another language, even if they're good at it, like an an.

40
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
We can call this speaking anxiety.

41
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Anxiety means an uncomfortable feeling or worry about something that is happening or could happen in the future.

42
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
So why does so many people have anxiety about speaking a foreign language?

43
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Experts think it's connected to the beliefs we have about ourselves.

44
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Han Duo, professor of Chinese, at La Payette College in the United States, explains more to BBC learning English presenter Georgie.

45
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:56.000
You know, usually the beliefs that cause anxiety, especially severe anxiety, are we call it irrational beliefs.

46
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And also like some low self perceptions, fear of negative evaluation, all those learner internal factors.

47
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And Han says that learners worry about mistakes because they're scared of negative evaluation.

48
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
In other words, that people will judge them for them mistakes and think badly of them.

49
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Han argues that irrational beliefs can make us anxious.

50
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Eurasian beliefs are beliefs that aren't based on things that are true. They're not logical.

51
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
There's some people who have speaking anxiety have low self perceptions.

52
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Your self perception is what you think about yourself.

53
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Self perception and irrational beliefs are both internal factors.

54
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
They come from inside your head, not from the people around you.

55
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So for example, when you speak your first language, you might feel confident and intelligent.

56
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But when you speak in a new language, you make mistakes and feel less confident.

57
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
You can't show people what you're really like. And this is frustrating.

58
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
But as we tell people all the time at BBC Learning English, mistakes are normal.

59
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
You have to try to speak even though you make mistakes.

60
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And mistakes can be a good thing. They can help us learn.

61
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:20.000
And if you want more tips to improve your speaking, listen to the beating speaking anxiety podcast.

62
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
There's a link in the notes below this episode.

63
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.000
But Beth, I think it's time for the answer to your quiz question.

64
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Yes, I asked you how many words does the average English speaker use in daily communication?

65
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
The answer is 20 to 30,000.

66
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
That's quite a lot. Yeah, that's loads.

67
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned.

68
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Pretty can be used as a modifier to mean quite or a bit.

69
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
If you relate to a person or situation, you understand them.

70
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Usually because you've experienced something similar.

71
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.000
Anxiety is feeling uncomfortable or worried about something that is happening or could happen in the future.

72
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.000
A rational beliefs are beliefs about something that is not true. They're not logical.

73
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Self-perception is the way you see yourself.

74
00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And internal means inside the body or mind.

75
00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

76
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
But if you'd like to find out more about speaking anxiety,

77
00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
then head over to our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

78
00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
to find our beating speaking anxiety series.

79
00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
There are podcasts about the things we find scary when speaking a different language

80
00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
and videos with tips to help you feel more confident with speaking.

81
00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Thanks for joining us and goodbye.

82
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Goodbye.
